1
00:00:05,457 --> 00:00:08,921
Now, here we want to talk
about the main features

2
00:00:08,921 --> 00:00:11,765
of urban transportation management.

3
00:00:12,181 --> 00:00:17,133
We will do so by distinguishing
between the performance dimension,

4
00:00:17,133 --> 00:00:22,812
the management of the different
transportation modes and infrastructures,

5
00:00:22,812 --> 00:00:25,951
and, at the end,
we will actually ask the question

6
00:00:25,951 --> 00:00:30,469
of who is really in charge
of the urban transportation system.

7
00:00:32,058 --> 00:00:34,575
Now, the main performance dimensions.

8
00:00:34,575 --> 00:00:37,994
There are actually
two such dimensions, and those are:

9
00:00:37,994 --> 00:00:43,651
this is the performance of the urban
transportation system as a whole.

10
00:00:43,651 --> 00:00:47,877
We're not talking here
about the performance of the bus,

11
00:00:47,877 --> 00:00:49,672
or the taxi, or something like that.

12
00:00:49,672 --> 00:00:51,749
We're talking about the performance

13
00:00:51,749 --> 00:00:55,486
of the overall
urban transportation system.

14
00:00:56,427 --> 00:01:00,212
Now, the first criteria
really is efficiency--

15
00:01:00,212 --> 00:01:03,763
how efficient is that system?

16
00:01:03,763 --> 00:01:07,328
How much time do you actually need?

17
00:01:07,328 --> 00:01:12,667
How much time do you spend
in the urban transportation system?

18
00:01:12,667 --> 00:01:15,918
This relates to congestion,

19
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:19,479
the congestion of the overall system,

20
00:01:19,479 --> 00:01:23,522
and, of course,
also about the reliability,

21
00:01:23,522 --> 00:01:25,729
the plannability of that.

22
00:01:25,729 --> 00:01:27,492
You may take a little longer,

23
00:01:27,492 --> 00:01:31,231
but you are sure it's going
to take you that much time,

24
00:01:31,231 --> 00:01:34,617
is different from, say, "Okay,
sometimes it takes me half an hour.

25
00:01:34,617 --> 00:01:37,081
Sometimes it takes me one hour."

26
00:01:37,081 --> 00:01:42,295
So this is the time efficiency
of the urban transportation.

27
00:01:42,295 --> 00:01:45,815
Then there is an energy-efficiency issue.

28
00:01:45,815 --> 00:01:49,895
We have seen that 30%
of global energy consumption

29
00:01:49,895 --> 00:01:55,073
is actually used by transport,
by urban transport,

30
00:01:55,073 --> 00:01:59,511
and 25% of the CO2 emissions of a city

31
00:01:59,511 --> 00:02:01,881
stem directly from transport,

32
00:02:01,881 --> 00:02:07,586
so the efficiency question here is
how much energy do you consume?

33
00:02:07,586 --> 00:02:09,434
Can you reduce that?

34
00:02:09,434 --> 00:02:12,509
Can you get the same
transportation service

35
00:02:12,509 --> 00:02:16,503
with less energy consumed,
and can you pollute less?

36
00:02:16,979 --> 00:02:19,567
And the third efficiency criteria,
of course,

37
00:02:19,567 --> 00:02:22,539
is the economic criteria of cost.

38
00:02:22,539 --> 00:02:27,407
How cost-effective is
your urban transportation system?

39
00:02:27,407 --> 00:02:31,788
Compared to how much you pay for it,

40
00:02:31,788 --> 00:02:35,533
how many services
do you actually get out of it?

41
00:02:35,533 --> 00:02:38,973
And, as we know,
there are two types of payments.

42
00:02:38,973 --> 00:02:43,171
There are prices for the transport,
and then there are subsidies

43
00:02:43,171 --> 00:02:45,806
by the public authorities
for this transport,

44
00:02:45,806 --> 00:02:50,125
but in both cases
it's an efficiency question, of course.

45
00:02:51,354 --> 00:02:55,056
The second important criteria is

46
00:02:55,056 --> 00:02:58,656
the attractiveness of public transport,

47
00:02:58,656 --> 00:03:02,169
of urban public transport
vis-Ă -vis the car.

48
00:03:04,433 --> 00:03:10,315
It is given that urban public transport
should substitute,

49
00:03:10,315 --> 00:03:14,185
as much as possible, the car,

50
00:03:14,185 --> 00:03:20,558
and here the question is,
how accessible is urban public transport?

51
00:03:21,441 --> 00:03:24,068
Do you have a bus stand all...

52
00:03:24,068 --> 00:03:27,928
The generally agreed idea today is
that somehow,

53
00:03:27,928 --> 00:03:30,223
within five-minutes' walking distance,

54
00:03:30,223 --> 00:03:34,968
you should have the ability to access

55
00:03:34,968 --> 00:03:41,034
a bus or a metro, or a bike stand,
or something like this,

56
00:03:41,034 --> 00:03:46,399
and so the accessibility is one
of the first criteria of attractiveness.

57
00:03:46,399 --> 00:03:50,264
The second criterion is the affordability:

58
00:03:50,264 --> 00:03:54,367
how affordable is that system?
And affordability--

59
00:03:54,367 --> 00:03:57,715
as we have discussed before,
in a previous block--

60
00:03:57,715 --> 00:04:01,220
affordability is very much related
to social criteria.

61
00:04:01,220 --> 00:04:03,268
It may be affordable for rich people,

62
00:04:03,268 --> 00:04:05,237
but not affordable for poor people.

63
00:04:05,237 --> 00:04:09,871
You want to make urban public transport
affordable for everyone.

64
00:04:11,313 --> 00:04:14,472
The third element here is
the intermodality.

65
00:04:14,803 --> 00:04:18,338
What sense does it make
